      <h1>How Many Steps in a Mile? (Walking and Running)</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Whether you are tracking your daily step count for fitness, training for a race, or simply curious about how far your walks actually take you, knowing the relationship between steps and miles is incredibly useful. The quick answer is that the average adult takes approximately 2,000 steps per mile while walking and about 1,400 steps per mile while running. But these numbers vary significantly based on your height, stride length, speed, and gait. This comprehensive guide provides detailed tables for every height, explains the walking versus running difference, shows you how to measure your personal stride, and breaks down how many calories you burn per mile at different paces.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>Quick Answer: Steps Per Mile</h2>
    <p>For a quick reference, here are the average steps per mile for different activities:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Walking (moderate pace, 3.0 mph):</strong> approximately 2,000 to 2,400 steps per mile</li>
      <li><strong>Brisk walking (4.0 mph):</strong> approximately 1,800 to 2,200 steps per mile</li>
      <li><strong>Jogging (5.0 mph):</strong> approximately 1,400 to 1,700 steps per mile</li>
      <li><strong>Running (6.0 to 7.0 mph):</strong> approximately 1,200 to 1,500 steps per mile</li>
      <li><strong>Fast running (8.0+ mph):</strong> approximately 1,000 to 1,300 steps per mile</li>
    </ul>
    <p>These averages assume a person of roughly average height (5 feet 7 inches for men and 5 feet 4 inches for women in the United States). Your personal numbers may differ by 10 to 20 percent based on your specific height and stride characteristics. For precise pace calculations, use our <a href="/pace/">pace calculator</a>.</p>

    <h2>Steps Per Mile by Height: Walking</h2>
