    <p>Running steps per mile decrease further as speed increases. Elite marathon runners, who typically run at 12 to 13 miles per hour, may take as few as 1,000 to 1,100 steps per mile due to their extremely long strides. Sprinters covering 100 meters may take only 42 to 48 steps total.</p>

    <h2>Walking vs. Running: Why the Step Count Differs</h2>
    <p>The fundamental biomechanical difference between walking and running explains why step counts per mile are so different for each activity.</p>
    <p>When you walk, at least one foot is always in contact with the ground. Your stride length is limited by your leg length and the need to maintain balance during the single-support phase (when one foot is on the ground and the other is swinging forward). Walking stride length is typically 40 to 45 percent of your height.</p>
    <p>When you run, there is a flight phase — a brief moment when both feet are off the ground. This flight phase allows you to cover additional horizontal distance with each stride. Running stride length is typically 60 to 70 percent of your height, and it increases further as speed increases. At a full sprint, elite athletes achieve stride lengths of 7 to 8 feet.</p>
    <p>The transition from walking to running typically occurs at speeds of about 4.5 to 5.0 miles per hour. At this speed, it becomes more energy-efficient to run than to walk because the walking gait becomes increasingly awkward and inefficient at higher speeds.</p>

    <h2>How to Measure Your Personal Stride Length</h2>
    <p>While the tables above provide good estimates, measuring your actual stride length gives you the most accurate steps-per-mile number. Here are three methods, from simplest to most precise:</p>

    <h3>Method 1: The 10-Step Method</h3>
    <p>This is the quickest approach and works well for a rough estimate. Find a flat, straight surface. Place a piece of tape on the ground as your starting point. Walk 10 normal steps at your usual pace. Place another piece of tape where your 10th step lands. Measure the total distance in feet and divide by 10. For example, if you covered 25 feet in 10 steps, your stride length is 2.5 feet. To find your steps per mile, divide 5,280 (feet in a mile) by your stride length: 5,280 divided by 2.5 equals 2,112 steps per mile.</p>

    <h3>Method 2: The Track Method</h3>
    <p>For greater accuracy, go to a standard 400-meter (quarter-mile) running track. Walk one full lap at your normal pace while counting every step. If you count 520 steps for one lap, then your steps per mile is 520 times 4, which equals 2,080 steps per mile. Your stride length is 5,280 divided by 2,080, which equals approximately 2.54 feet. Repeat for two or three laps and average the results for better accuracy.</p>

    <h3>Method 3: The GPS Method</h3>
    <p>Use a GPS-enabled fitness watch or smartphone app. Walk a known route (ideally at least half a mile for accuracy) while the device counts your steps and measures distance via GPS. Divide the total distance in feet by the total steps counted. Most modern fitness trackers will calculate your stride length automatically after enough walking data is collected and display it in their companion app.</p>

